WEBVTT

00:03.580 --> 00:05.290
Previously on "How To Get Away
With Murder"...

00:05.290 --> 00:06.750
I'm Jacqueline Roa,
Isaac's ex-wife.

00:06.750 --> 00:08.120
Your situation
is triggering him.

00:08.120 --> 00:09.460
Did you give Stella
those drugs?

00:09.460 --> 00:10.710
Jacqueline, this is
Annalise Keating!

00:10.710 --> 00:11.880
I swear to God,
put the phone down!

00:11.880 --> 00:13.540
Ask him about Stella.

00:13.540 --> 00:15.880
How'd you know
Christophe?

00:15.880 --> 00:18.290
Get the hell out of here!

00:18.290 --> 00:19.250
You have more than
enough plaintiffs.

00:19.250 --> 00:21.000
I want to make him
my face case!

00:21.000 --> 00:22.750
-He's in.
-There's no chance in hell

00:22.750 --> 00:24.670
the Supreme Court is
going to hear this case!

00:24.670 --> 00:26.170
-You just need to ask for help!

00:28.580 --> 00:30.540
Annalise:
The Department of Justice

00:30.540 --> 00:33.670
recommends a maximum
of 150 cases at a time,

00:33.670 --> 00:36.710
but the PD's in Pennsylvania
carry a load of over 200.

00:36.710 --> 00:39.000
This is an issue for the
state legislature, Ms. Keating.

00:39.000 --> 00:41.120
Public defenders need to
demand better funding.

00:41.120 --> 00:43.670
But the money isn't there,
thus leading to long-term,

00:43.670 --> 00:45.620
systematic violations
of the Sixth Amendment.

00:45.620 --> 00:48.670
But the justices in Pennsylvania
wrote that forcing counties

00:48.670 --> 00:51.750
to provide more funding violates
the separation of powers.

00:51.750 --> 00:53.250
In Johnson v. Zerbst,

00:53.250 --> 00:55.750
this Court established
Sixth Amendment violations,

00:55.750 --> 00:58.000
not as a states' issue
or federal issue,

00:58.000 --> 00:59.250
but a human-rights issue.

00:59.250 --> 01:02.080
Believe me, Noah,
I am thrilled

01:02.080 --> 01:04.040
for any chance
to argue a case

01:04.040 --> 01:05.330
in front of our nation's
greatest court.

01:05.330 --> 01:07.000
You've won four cases
there before.

01:07.000 --> 01:09.830
Because I study the Court
and its nuances,

01:09.830 --> 01:11.750
and the only reason they agreed
to even hear this case

01:11.750 --> 01:14.420
is because Ms. Keating has
made friends with some
very influential people.

01:14.420 --> 01:16.120
You're referring to
President Fitzgerald Grant?

01:16.120 --> 01:17.830
Amongst others.

01:17.830 --> 01:20.420
I can't believe that
you're on a first-name
basis with Olivia Pope.

01:20.420 --> 01:21.960
I know her name.
I doubt she remembers mine.

01:21.960 --> 01:24.290
Look, I'm just saying we all
have enough to feel guilty about

01:24.290 --> 01:25.420
without you adding that
to the pile.

01:26.830 --> 01:28.580
What does that mean?

01:28.580 --> 01:30.080
"We all have enough
to feel guilty about"?

01:30.080 --> 01:32.710
Simon, Wes,
all the murder.

01:32.710 --> 01:35.750
Look.
It's nice that you feel bad

01:35.750 --> 01:37.380
about stealing the case
from Connor,

01:37.380 --> 01:39.040
but it was your idea
to on-board the Pope.

01:39.040 --> 01:40.790
And besides, what were
you supposed to do?

01:40.790 --> 01:43.960
Tell AK to send Connor
to D.C. instead of you?

01:43.960 --> 01:46.380
I mean, what kind of lean-out
crap would that be

01:48.960 --> 01:50.420
Of course
you get to be mad.

01:50.420 --> 01:53.210
Class action was never about me.
It's about the plaintiffs.

01:53.210 --> 01:56.250
Well, then, prove it and come
to D.C. with the rest of us.

01:56.250 --> 01:58.380
I have to beg the dean
to let me re-enroll.

01:59.670 --> 02:02.790
This is a once-in-a-lifetime
opportunity to watch Annalise

02:02.790 --> 02:05.170
yell at a bunch
of old white dudes!

02:05.170 --> 02:06.960
And we could
check out the monuments

02:06.960 --> 02:09.580
and go look for closet cases
on the Hill.

02:09.580 --> 02:10.420
Okay, fine. I'll go.

02:10.420 --> 02:12.710
Yay!

02:12.710 --> 02:13.920
Field trip! Mwah!

02:13.920 --> 02:16.290
-Yay.

02:16.290 --> 02:18.170
Annalise: These
Sixth Amendment violations

02:18.170 --> 02:19.620
are a form of
disenfranchisement,

02:19.620 --> 02:21.620
primarily affecting
people of color.

02:21.620 --> 02:24.670
Are you implying that
the Commonwealth intended

02:24.670 --> 02:27.500
its denial of state funding to
have a racially biased effect?

02:27.500 --> 02:29.920
I'm not implying it.
I'm flat-out stating it.

02:29.920 --> 02:32.250
6.5% of Americans
are black men,

02:32.250 --> 02:34.580
and yet they account for 40%
of the prison population.

02:34.580 --> 02:36.790
Stop. You list those
statistics in your brief.

02:36.790 --> 02:38.290
Refer the Justices there

02:38.290 --> 02:40.750
so you don't waste a second
of your 30 minutes.

02:40.750 --> 02:43.460
I can't say it enough --
every word matters.

02:47.250 --> 02:49.750
Annalise!

02:49.750 --> 02:52.580
Oh, sorry.

02:52.580 --> 02:55.880
I thought they stopped
the investigation into Isaac.

02:55.880 --> 02:57.420
Bonnie: They did.

02:57.420 --> 02:59.920
Then why can't we get
his testimony reinstated?

02:59.920 --> 03:03.880
Isaac isn't
a reliable expert anymore.

03:03.880 --> 03:06.380
-That's all I can tell you.

03:06.380 --> 03:08.380
But even if our states
could find

03:08.380 --> 03:10.380
more funding
for public defenders,

03:10.380 --> 03:12.500
what about using that money
for our schools?

03:12.500 --> 03:13.920
Or housing
for the homeless?

03:13.920 --> 03:15.620
What about the millions
of children in the

03:15.620 --> 03:17.210
foster-care system that
are wards of the state?

03:17.210 --> 03:18.380
I'm sorry you're
not there with her.

03:18.380 --> 03:21.000
Or women who depend
on state funds

03:21.000 --> 03:22.790
to escape
battered housing.

03:22.790 --> 03:24.540
And let's not forget --

03:24.540 --> 03:27.380
my opposing counsel was just
a criminal defendant herself.

03:27.380 --> 03:29.710
Ms. Keating was cleared
of all charges.

03:29.710 --> 03:31.920
In fact, she says that it was
her own experience in jail

03:31.920 --> 03:33.710
that inspired
this class action.

03:33.710 --> 03:35.330
Well, I would make up
that story, too,

03:35.330 --> 03:36.580
if I were in her shoes.
Look what just came.

03:36.580 --> 03:38.420
Ohh. Is he trying
to win you back?

03:38.420 --> 03:40.620
It's for you.

03:40.620 --> 03:42.080
...agree that it's beneficial
to rid our prisons

03:42.080 --> 03:43.710
of people
who don't deserve...

03:43.710 --> 03:46.880
...draw the line
between guilty...

03:46.880 --> 03:51.330
Hmm. You should hide that before
I find a way to shotgun it.

03:51.330 --> 03:52.830
Explain to me how

03:52.830 --> 03:54.880
someone who was just fired
from teaching the law

03:54.880 --> 03:56.960
can be entrusted to change it.
It's ludicrous.

03:56.960 --> 03:58.460
She's trying to
get in your head.

03:58.460 --> 03:59.790
I've heard worse.

03:59.790 --> 04:02.330
And then,
there is Olivia Pope,

04:02.330 --> 04:04.830
a woman well known for
finding ways around the law,

04:04.830 --> 04:06.670
not protecting it.

04:06.670 --> 04:09.540
So my concern is that
these two women,

04:09.540 --> 04:11.580
claiming to fight
for the poor,

04:11.580 --> 04:13.620
might actually
just be using this case

04:13.620 --> 04:16.120
to distract us from
their own criminal acts.

04:16.120 --> 04:18.380
Let's not go
below the belt.

04:18.380 --> 04:20.540
Uh, talk to me about
some of your --

04:22.080 --> 04:24.750
It's kill or be killed.

04:24.750 --> 04:26.210
You do know that.

04:27.500 --> 04:30.120
I know it,
and I look forward to it.

04:31.620 --> 04:33.960
Let's get back to work.

04:41.080 --> 04:44.170
Nate: I got something good
to tell you for once.

04:44.170 --> 04:46.460
There's no such thing
as good in here.

04:46.460 --> 04:48.120
Annalise appealed
the state's decision,

04:48.120 --> 04:51.460
and the Supreme Court
agreed to hear your case.

04:51.460 --> 04:53.670
That means she needs you
at the table with her.

04:53.670 --> 04:56.880
No way the warden's gonna
approve me leaving here.

04:56.880 --> 04:58.080
He already approved it.

04:59.960 --> 05:02.290
You're going to
the Supreme Court.

05:02.290 --> 05:08.290
♪♪

05:08.670 --> 05:14.710
♪♪

05:29.420 --> 05:31.170
Jacqueline won't stop
calling me.

05:31.170 --> 05:33.000
-Okay.
-No, it's not okay.

05:33.000 --> 05:34.330
Have you heard anything?

05:34.330 --> 05:35.830
Denver's not gonna
re-open Isaac's case.

05:35.830 --> 05:37.500
How are you feeling?

05:37.500 --> 05:38.790
Fine.

05:38.790 --> 05:40.250
You're allowed to be
a little nervous.

05:40.250 --> 05:42.670
I'm not nervous.
I just want to win.

05:42.670 --> 05:45.500
You're going to.

05:45.500 --> 05:48.290
Did you invite your mom?
Bonnie, she'd pee herself

05:48.290 --> 05:50.170
right in the middle
of the Supreme Court.

05:50.170 --> 05:51.710
You think that's what
I want to be worrying about

05:51.710 --> 05:53.670
at the podium?

05:53.670 --> 05:59.710
♪♪

06:01.920 --> 06:07.920
♪♪

06:10.330 --> 06:16.330
♪♪

06:18.540 --> 06:24.540
♪♪

06:26.960 --> 06:32.960
♪♪

06:35.380 --> 06:37.250
Olivia: Good news.

06:40.460 --> 06:42.830
Ingrid Egan's interview

06:42.830 --> 06:45.880
had the opposite effect
of what she intended.

06:45.880 --> 06:50.170
So now the ACLU, the NAACP,
and Public Counsel

06:50.170 --> 06:52.620
are all offering
to come on board.

06:52.620 --> 06:54.460
No.

06:54.460 --> 06:56.380
These are attorneys
who have argued

06:56.380 --> 06:58.710
and won many cases
in this Court.

06:58.710 --> 07:01.380
Then, how come I'm the
one that got the case
this far and not them?

07:01.380 --> 07:05.790
♪♪

07:05.790 --> 07:07.830
Anna Mae Harkness.

07:07.830 --> 07:10.830
Born in Memphis in 1967.

07:10.830 --> 07:13.580
Attended junior college for
two years, then university,

07:13.580 --> 07:14.880
then law school,

07:14.880 --> 07:17.580
where she was one of
just 20 women in her class

07:17.580 --> 07:21.960
and one of only two black
students in the entire school.

07:21.960 --> 07:23.620
And in alumnae interview,
she's quoted as saying

07:23.620 --> 07:26.000
a career goal
was to argue a case

07:26.000 --> 07:27.210
before the United States
Supreme Court.

07:27.210 --> 07:28.420
And win.

07:28.420 --> 07:30.670
And win.

07:30.670 --> 07:33.790
What the hell
are you saying?

07:33.790 --> 07:37.170
If you lose this case,

07:37.170 --> 07:39.420
it'll set criminal-justice
reform back decades.

07:39.420 --> 07:41.000
You don't think
I know that?

07:41.000 --> 07:43.080
Then think about
accepting some help.

07:43.080 --> 07:45.790
That's all I'm suggesting.

07:48.670 --> 07:50.040
Where are you going?

07:53.420 --> 07:56.580
Take a moment.

07:56.580 --> 07:58.210
Soak in the glory.

08:00.330 --> 08:03.500
God knows it won't be
like this on game day.

08:03.500 --> 08:08.250
♪♪

08:08.250 --> 08:13.040
♪♪

08:13.040 --> 08:17.830
♪♪

08:17.830 --> 08:22.620
♪♪

08:22.620 --> 08:27.670
♪♪

08:29.500 --> 08:31.960
♪♪

08:33.830 --> 08:38.000
♪♪

08:38.000 --> 08:40.960
Mama.

08:40.960 --> 08:43.120
It's Anna Mae.

08:51.460 --> 08:54.250
What is the point
of having a burner phone

08:54.250 --> 08:56.580
if you're just gonna
force me to meet you at work?

08:56.580 --> 08:58.460
I talked to Laurel's mom.

08:58.460 --> 09:00.040
What?

09:00.040 --> 09:02.620
I showed her the photo, and
she just started talking --

09:02.620 --> 09:05.170
about how Laurel
called her last year,

09:05.170 --> 09:07.620
told her she was in love
with this guy, Wes.

09:07.620 --> 09:09.210
Don't tell me you
believe any of this.

09:09.210 --> 09:11.040
I'm just telling you
what she told me,

09:11.040 --> 09:12.960
which is that she had
Dominick set up a meeting

09:12.960 --> 09:14.380
between her and the puppy

09:14.380 --> 09:16.620
so she could pay him 100K
to stay away from Laurel.

09:18.880 --> 09:20.330
That doesn't make sense.

09:20.330 --> 09:22.750
Especially since
I can't find the money.

09:22.750 --> 09:24.750
No.

09:24.750 --> 09:27.290
Just look into Wes'
old bank account, see
if there's money there.

09:27.290 --> 09:30.500
And when there's not?
You'll finally tell Laurel?

09:30.500 --> 09:32.540
Okay.

09:34.920 --> 09:36.750
I'll let you know
what I find.

09:36.750 --> 09:42.750
♪♪

09:46.830 --> 09:48.710
So, have we made
a decision?

09:48.710 --> 09:49.920
I have.

09:51.750 --> 09:53.880
I'm doing it.
On my own.

09:53.880 --> 09:56.330
Good.

09:56.330 --> 09:58.000
I'm not in the mood
to make new friends.

09:58.000 --> 10:00.920
Unfortunately, it appears

10:00.920 --> 10:02.710
our opposing counsel
is all about it.

10:02.710 --> 10:05.250
What does that mean?
I got word Ingrid Egan

10:05.250 --> 10:07.880
is trading information
with one of the Justices.

10:07.880 --> 10:10.170
-We don't know.

10:10.170 --> 10:11.880
I tasked Marcus and
Michaela to find out.

10:14.000 --> 10:15.580
You expecting company?

10:15.580 --> 10:18.540
Oh. My parents. Give me a second
to get rid of them.

10:19.960 --> 10:23.380
Diana Ross!

10:24.670 --> 10:26.670
I just mean that my baby

10:26.670 --> 10:29.330
is singing
with the Supremes!

10:31.040 --> 10:32.750
Mac: They got you set up
in the fancy suite, huh?

10:32.750 --> 10:34.920
I put myself
in this fancy suite.

10:34.920 --> 10:36.920
Who's this?

10:36.920 --> 10:39.750
Olivia Pope. I'm working with
your daughter on her case.

10:39.750 --> 10:41.250
Wait a minute. What'd
you say your name was?

10:41.250 --> 10:43.120
-Mama.
-I didn't ask you.

10:43.120 --> 10:45.170
I asked her.
What's your name, baby?

10:45.170 --> 10:46.960
Olivia Pope.

10:46.960 --> 10:49.960
I'm just messing
with you. I know who you are.

10:49.960 --> 10:53.540
Didn't I tell you, the lady
from the TV was gonna be here!

10:53.540 --> 10:55.500
It's an honor to
meet you, Miss Pope.

10:55.500 --> 10:57.120
The honor
is all mine, sir.

10:57.120 --> 10:59.620
All right. I got you set up
in a room down the hall.

10:59.620 --> 11:01.040
Just --
Let's get you settled.

11:01.040 --> 11:02.540
Not before you get
some food in you.

11:02.540 --> 11:04.960
I fixed some stew and
biscuits this morning.

11:04.960 --> 11:06.420
Mama, we got work to do.

11:06.420 --> 11:08.830
But you need fuel
for that work.

11:08.830 --> 11:10.380
Get out the
Tupperware, Daddy.

11:10.380 --> 11:12.710
Mac: Already on it.

11:12.710 --> 11:18.710
♪♪

11:19.120 --> 11:25.120
♪♪

11:25.830 --> 11:28.250
Michaela,
this is a stakeout.

11:28.250 --> 11:30.580
Two sets of eyes
are better than one.

11:30.580 --> 11:32.460
Our opposing counsel isn't
stupid enough to have

11:32.460 --> 11:35.920
a Supreme Court Justice
visit her house in
the middle of the day.

11:35.920 --> 11:38.460
Are you calling
my plan stupid?

11:38.460 --> 11:41.750
♪♪

11:43.330 --> 11:45.120
I have a boyfriend,
Marcus.

11:45.120 --> 11:47.250
-Asher. I know.
-I know you know.

11:47.250 --> 11:49.460
Which is why I need
to make it clear

11:49.460 --> 11:52.120
because I love Asher
very much,

11:52.120 --> 11:55.790
even though you are obviously
charming and intelligent

11:55.790 --> 11:57.420
and everything I ever
thought I wanted in a man.

11:57.420 --> 12:00.170
-Okay.
-Good.

12:00.170 --> 12:02.210
Oliver:
Every minute we wait,

12:02.210 --> 12:03.500
traffic's only
getting worse, Asher.

12:03.500 --> 12:05.380
-I'm moving my tush!
-Or we could just not go.

12:05.380 --> 12:07.710
We already lost our tickets
to Annalise's parents, so --

12:07.710 --> 12:09.790
We'll get tickets as long
as we get up at the crack
of dawn for the line.

12:09.790 --> 12:12.920
Plus, I have the perfect thing
for us to do while we wait.

12:12.920 --> 12:15.620
-Wedding planning.
-We're not having a wedding.

12:15.620 --> 12:17.120
Uh, you are, too.
I witnessed the proposal.

12:17.120 --> 12:20.790
We're getting married.
We're just not wasting
money on a DJ and bad cake.

12:20.790 --> 12:23.330
That sounds like some
internalized homophobia to me.

12:23.330 --> 12:25.080
Laurel: Hey.

12:25.080 --> 12:26.830
Sorry I'm late.

12:26.830 --> 12:28.210
Laurel, tell Connor and Oliver
they need to have a wedding.

12:28.210 --> 12:29.790
You need to have
a wedding.

12:29.790 --> 12:32.460
See? It's the only thing giving
anyone any J-O-Y right now.

12:32.460 --> 12:34.040
Can we please
debate this in the car?

12:34.040 --> 12:35.540
95's already
really, really red.

12:35.540 --> 12:38.040
Okay.

12:40.790 --> 12:43.460
I tell you.
I've seen them everywhere.

12:43.460 --> 12:45.330
Women, women everywhere.

12:45.330 --> 12:47.880
The grocery stores,
doctor's office,

12:47.880 --> 12:50.540
church, everywhere.

12:50.540 --> 12:53.830
It's because cops keep
sending the men off to jail.

12:53.830 --> 12:58.330
No wonder Anna Mae ran off
and married a white man.

12:58.330 --> 13:00.170
-Okay. Lunch is over.

13:00.170 --> 13:05.170
I'm just saying, thank God
for both of you, mm?

13:05.170 --> 13:10.120
This country's been broken
for damn near my whole life.

13:10.120 --> 13:11.620
Huh?

13:11.620 --> 13:13.210
I'm just grateful
to see somebody

13:13.210 --> 13:15.210
who can possibly fix it.

13:15.210 --> 13:16.960
Your daughter deserves
most of the credit

13:16.960 --> 13:18.880
for this case,
Mrs. Harkness.

13:18.880 --> 13:20.330
And you deserve credit

13:20.330 --> 13:22.290
for being smart enough
to team up with her.

13:24.250 --> 13:25.580
What's wrong?
Is it your father?

13:25.580 --> 13:27.250
They're driving him down
in the morning.

13:27.250 --> 13:28.580
I just came to see
how you're feeling.

13:28.580 --> 13:29.830
Nathaniel.

13:29.830 --> 13:32.380
Miss Ophelia.

13:32.380 --> 13:34.500
-How good to see you.
-So good to see you again, too.

13:34.500 --> 13:35.960
Sir.

13:35.960 --> 13:38.080
Oh, you know better than
to call me that, son.

13:38.080 --> 13:40.920
Olivia,
Nathaniel Lahey.

13:40.920 --> 13:42.040
You can call me Nate.

13:42.040 --> 13:44.170
Nate Lahey?

13:44.170 --> 13:46.460
Not the face-case guy.
I'm his son.

13:49.380 --> 13:52.830
Our face case is your
ex

13:52.830 --> 13:55.120
And your ex-boyfriend
was the president, and you
don't hear me judging.

13:55.120 --> 13:56.290
These people
we're up against,

13:56.290 --> 13:58.580
they're looking for
anything to crucify us.

13:58.580 --> 14:00.290
Us or me?
You heard that woman
on the news.

14:00.290 --> 14:02.290
I am as much
a target here as you.

14:02.290 --> 14:04.380
Is that why you asked me to
bring on those other lawyers?

14:04.380 --> 14:07.120
-I left that decision to you.
-And I made it as I saw fit.

14:07.120 --> 14:09.460
Now I'm going back inside.

14:09.460 --> 14:11.210
To work or to eat
your mama's stew?

14:13.880 --> 14:15.620
You're terrified, huh?

14:15.620 --> 14:18.170
Having to rely on my messy ass
to save your reputation.

14:18.170 --> 14:19.790
Your reputation.

14:19.790 --> 14:21.250
And I don't understand

14:21.250 --> 14:23.750
how inviting distraction
into your life

14:23.750 --> 14:27.080
the day before the biggest case
of your career is a good idea.

14:27.080 --> 14:28.580
That distraction
is my family.

14:28.580 --> 14:30.040
What about your
plaintiffs' families?
You know what?

14:30.040 --> 14:32.380
I let you do your thing, but
this is my world, my rules.

14:32.380 --> 14:34.500
So stop worrying about
me being prepared.

14:34.500 --> 14:35.790
I am worried.

14:35.790 --> 14:38.500
About me losing or
it reflecting badly on you?

14:38.500 --> 14:42.080
Both.

14:42.080 --> 14:44.080
You know, this isn't about

14:44.080 --> 14:47.620
a bucket list
or saving my reputation.

14:47.620 --> 14:51.580
It's about knowing that I've
done something that matters.

14:51.580 --> 14:53.250
And I know that
you want it, too,

14:53.250 --> 14:55.250
because I can
see it in you.

14:55.250 --> 14:57.710
That's why I asked
my family to be here

14:57.710 --> 14:59.750
and why I asked you
to be here.

14:59.750 --> 15:04.620
Because winning this case
will matter to me like...

15:07.290 --> 15:10.120
...nothing in my life
ever has.

15:10.120 --> 15:13.500
So stop worrying about me.

15:13.500 --> 15:16.000
Stop handling me

15:16.000 --> 15:20.540
and let me do my job
the best way I know how.

15:24.000 --> 15:26.790
Okay.

15:26.790 --> 15:29.750
[ Kid Cudi's
"Swim in the Light" plays ]

15:29.750 --> 15:33.580
♪♪

15:33.580 --> 15:35.420
♪ You could try
and numb the pain ♪

15:36.540 --> 15:41.290
